                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t17950916-85-off479 t17950916-85-victim919"></join>
                  </persName>
               
            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17950916-85-person920">
                  ANGUS
                   CAMERON
               <interp inst="t17950916-85-person920" type="surname" value="CAMERON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17950916-85-person920" type="given" value="ANGUS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17950916-85-person920" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I live in Beet-street, near Golden-square.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you lose a cloth coat at any time? - Yes, from <placeName id="t17950916-85-crimeloc481">the Bricklayer's Arms, King-street, Golden-square</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t17950916-85-crimeloc481" type="placeName" value="the Bricklayer's Arms, King-street, Golden-square"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t17950916-85-crimeloc481" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17950916-85-off479 t17950916-85-crimeloc481"></join>; the taylor had it, and was coming home with it, and he happened to call in the public house; I was in the public house, and he put it down on the seat beside of him; it was in the parlour; he told me that he had got my great coat, and was going home with it; I told him I would take it home myself. The prisoner at the bar was smoaking his pipe in the parlour at the same time; he had used that house for a month before that, and never was out of it. When I was going home I asked the taylor where was the coat; and he put his hand behind him and did not find it, and there was nobody missed out of the room but the prisoner at the bar; we could not hear of him any more that night not the next day. I staid about an hour afterwards, but the coat was missed from about five minutes after he went out of the room; he never returned to the house; I never see him till last Monday week when he was apprehended.</p>
               <p>Q. What day were you at the Brick-layers Arms? - Saturday, the 15th of August, about eight o'clock at night. He was taken up in St. Giles's. The people that were in the room knew that he stole the coat.</p>
               <p>Q. Was the coat ever found? - No, it was not.</p>
               <p>Q. Are any people here that live in that public house? - No. When he was apprehended I told him if he would give me the duplicate of the coat, I would let him go about his business; he told me that he had sold it for four shillings and sixpence.</p>

               <p>Q. Did he say where? - He did not.</p>
               <p>Q. And he never said he had sold it till you told him it would be better for him to do so? - No.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17950916-85-person921">
                  JOHN
                   AUSTON
               <interp inst="t17950916-85-person921" type="surname" value="AUSTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17950916-85-person921" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17950916-85-person921" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>Q. Were you at the public house? - Yes.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you see the prisoner take away the coat? - I did not. I have known the house some time.</p>
               <p>Q. Had he frequented it any time? -He had.</p>
               <p>Q. Do you know whether he ever came to that house after the coat was missing? - I never see him there.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t17950916-85-verdict482" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17950916-85-verdict482" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
               Not GUILTY
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>Tried by the second Middlesex Jury before Mr. RECORDER.</p>
